# API Patterns

## Folder Responsibilities

```
api/src/
  agents/          ← LLM orchestration. Anything that calls an LLM lives here.
    prompts/       ← Shared prompt builders that are NOT part of the RAG assistant (e.g. profile AI snapshot).
    <agent-name>/
      prompts/     ← One file per prompt for that agent (RAG, contradiction, comms, …).
      pipeline.ts  ← Orchestrates: retrieve → prompt → LLM → output
      retriever.ts ← Retrieval step (embed query → similaritySearch)
      index.ts     ← Barrel export for the agent
  rag/             ← Pure data layer. No LLM calls. Ever.
    embeddings.ts  ← chunkText, embedChunks, storeEmbeddings, ingestCommunication
    index.ts
  db/
    client.ts      ← Prisma singleton
    vector.ts      ← Raw pgvector SQL helpers (similaritySearch)
  routes/          ← Thin Express routers. Validate input, resolve permissions, call services/agents.
  services/        ← Business logic over Prisma. No LLM. No direct SQL.
  middleware/      ← auth, attachUser, requireRole, validateBody
  pii/             ← PII scrubbing. No LLM. Pure string transforms.
  utils/           ← Shared non-domain helpers (serialize, etc.)
```

**Hard rule:** `rag/` never imports from `agents/`. `agents/` may import from `rag/` and `db/`. Routes never import directly from `agents/` internals — they go through the agent's `index.ts` barrel.

## Agent Structure

Every agent lives in `src/agents/<name>/`. The pattern is:

```
agents/
  prompts/
    student-history-snapshot.ts   ← profile AI Snapshot (JSON GET)
    student-profile-ai-streams.ts ← profile AI Summary tab (GET SSE actions)
  rag/
    prompts/
      rag-assistant.ts
    retriever.ts
    pipeline.ts
    index.ts
  contradiction/          ← Phase 5
    prompts/
      detect-contradiction.ts
    nodes/
      ingestNewComm.ts
      retrieveHistory.ts
      detectContradiction.ts
      applyFix.ts
      persist.ts
    graph.ts
    state.ts
    index.ts
```

## LLM Calls — Always Via LangChain

All LLM calls must go through `@langchain/openai` (or `@langchain/anthropic` when we switch to Claude), **never** the raw `openai` SDK. The `openai` package is reserved for `text-embedding-3-small` only.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — raw OpenAI SDK for chat
import OpenAI from "openai";
const openai = new OpenAI();
const res = await openai.chat.completions.create({ ... });

// ✅ GOOD — LangChain wrapper
import { ChatOpenAI } from "@langchain/openai";
import { SystemMessage, HumanMessage } from "@langchain/core/messages";
const llm = new ChatOpenAI({ model: "gpt-4o-mini", temperature: 0 });
const stream = await llm.stream([new SystemMessage(prompt), new HumanMessage(query)]);
```

LangChain's wrappers give us LangSmith tracing, streaming, and model-swappability for free. Switching from GPT to Claude (Phase 5 contradiction agent) is a one-line change.

## Prompts — Typed Builder Functions, Never Raw Strings

Every system prompt lives in a `prompts/` file inside its agent folder. It exports a typed function that accepts the context it needs and returns a `string`. No inline prompt assembly in pipeline or route files.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — inline prompt in pipeline
const systemPrompt = `You are a helpful assistant. Context: ${chunks.map(...).join("\n")}`;

// ✅ GOOD — dedicated prompt file
// agents/rag/prompts/rag-assistant.ts
export function buildRagSystemPrompt(chunks: SimilarityResult[]): string { ... }

// agents/rag/pipeline.ts
import { buildRagSystemPrompt } from "./prompts/rag-assistant.js";
const systemPrompt = buildRagSystemPrompt(chunks);
```

Benefits: prompts are independently readable, diffable, and testable.

## LLM Client — Lazy Singleton Per Agent

Each agent module holds its own lazily-instantiated LLM client. Do not instantiate at module load time — this allows the module to be imported in tests or seeding without requiring API keys.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD — lazy singleton
let _llm: ChatOpenAI | null = null;

function getLLM(): ChatOpenAI {
  if (!_llm) {
    const apiKey = process.env["OPENAI_API_KEY"];
    if (!apiKey) throw new Error("OPENAI_API_KEY is not set");
    _llm = new ChatOpenAI({ model: "gpt-4o-mini", streaming: true, temperature: 0 });
  }
  return _llm;
}
```

## SSE Streaming Format

All streaming endpoints write `data:` lines in this shape. The client can discriminate on `type`:

```typescript
{ type: "token";   content: string  }   // streamed token from LLM
{ type: "sources"; sources: RagSource[] }  // sent once after stream ends
{ type: "done"  }                        // terminal — client closes reader
{ type: "error";  message: string   }   // sent on any thrown error before res.end()
```

Required headers on any SSE response:
```typescript
res.setHeader("Content-Type", "text/event-stream");
res.setHeader("Cache-Control", "no-cache");
res.setHeader("Connection", "keep-alive");
res.setHeader("X-Accel-Buffering", "no");
res.flushHeaders();
```

## Permission Scoping — Routes Resolve, Agents Consume

Routes are responsible for resolving `studentIds` from `req.user`. Agents and retrievers accept an already-resolved `studentIds: string[]` and must never derive permissions themselves.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — agent doing permission work
async function retrieveRelevantChunks(query: string, userId: string) {
  const user = await prisma.user.findUnique({ where: { id: userId } });
  const studentIds = user.rosterIds;
  ...
}

// ✅ GOOD — route resolves, agent consumes
// route: const studentIds = await resolveStudentScope(req.user, studentId);
// agent: await retrieveRelevantChunks(query, studentIds);
```

## Service Layer Return Values

Services return string literal sentinels instead of throwing for expected failure modes. Routes pattern-match on them.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD — predictable, no try/catch in routes for expected cases
return "not_found" as const;
return "forbidden" as const;
return "conflict" as const;
```

## Error Response Shape — Always `{ error: { code, message } }`

Every JSON error response from any route must use this shape:

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — bare string, inconsistent shape
res.status(404).json({ error: "Not found" });
res.status(500).json({ error: message });

// ✅ GOOD — structured, discriminable by the client
res.status(404).json({ error: { code: "NOT_FOUND", message: "Student not found." } });
res.status(403).json({ error: { code: "FORBIDDEN", message: "You do not have access to this resource." } });
res.status(409).json({ error: { code: "CONFLICT", message: "A user with that email already exists." } });
```

Standard `code` values to use:

| HTTP | code | When |
|------|------|------|
| 400 | `INVALID_REQUEST` / `MISSING_PARAM` | Validation failures |
| 403 | `FORBIDDEN` | Access control rejections |
| 404 | `NOT_FOUND` | Resource not found |
| 409 | `CONFLICT` | Duplicate / constraint violation |
| 500 | `E500` | Unhandled (set by `errorHandler`) |

## Route Error Handling — `next(err)` for Everything Unhandled

Route handlers must only catch errors they explicitly know how to handle (i.e. service sentinel values). All unexpected exceptions must be forwarded to the global error handler via `next(err)` — never swallowed, never serialised inline.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — swallowing unexpected errors with a custom 500
router.get("/:id", async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const result = await getStudent(id, req.user!);
    res.json(result);
  } catch (err) {
    const message = err instanceof Error ? err.message : "Internal error";
    res.status(500).json({ error: message }); // ← leaks internals, wrong shape
  }
});

// ✅ GOOD — sentinel-only catch; unexpected errors go to next()
router.get("/:id", async (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {
  try {
    const result = await getStudent(id, req.user!);
    if (result === "not_found") {
      res.status(404).json({ error: { code: "NOT_FOUND", message: "Student not found." } });
      return;
    }
    res.json(result);
  } catch (err) {
    next(err); // ← global errorHandler in middleware/errorHandler.ts takes over
  }
});
```

The global `errorHandler` middleware (registered last in `app.ts`) formats all unhandled errors into the standard `{ error: { code, message } }` shape and redacts stack traces in production.

## Logging — Always Via `logger`, Never `console.*`

All logging must go through the shared pino singleton at `src/utils/logger.ts`. Never use `console.log`, `console.warn`, or `console.error` anywhere under `api/` (including `prisma/seed.ts` and `testAuth.ts`). Manual scripts should import `logger` the same as the server.

When a mailbox address must appear in a log field for debugging, use `maskEmailForLog()` from `src/utils/maskEmail.ts` — never log a full email.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
console.log("[scheduler] classroom sync failed", err);
console.error("[webhook] failed to decode message");

// ✅ GOOD
import logger from "../utils/logger.js";
logger.error({ job: "classroom-sync", err }, "cron job failed");
logger.warn({ mailbox: maskedMailbox }, "webhook received for unmonitored mailbox");
```

### Log Shape

Every log line is a JSON object with these fields:

| Field | Type | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `time` | ISO 8601 | pino built-in — always present |
| `level` | `info` \| `warn` \| `error` \| `debug` | |
| `service` | `"PROJECT_NAME_HERE-api"` | Replace `PROJECT_NAME_HERE` with your service slug; set globally in logger config — never set per call |
| `msg` | `string` | Human-readable event name — keep it concise and consistent |
| `...context` | object | Domain fields spread alongside `msg` — see table below |

### Levels

| Level | When to use |
|---|---|
| `debug` | Dev-only fine-grained internals. Never ships meaningful output in production (`LOG_LEVEL=info` by default). |
| `info` | Normal operational events: server started, cron ran, watch renewed, message ingested. |
| `warn` | Degraded but non-fatal: watch renewal failed for one mailbox, identity match flagged for review. |
| `error` | Failures requiring attention: unhandled exception, DB write failed, Google API 401/403. |

### Context Keys by Category

```typescript
// HTTP requests (added automatically by pino-http — do not add manually in routes)
{ req_id, method, path, status, duration_ms }

// Cron / scheduler
{ job: "gmail-watch-renewal" | "classroom-sync" | "drive-sync", duration_ms }

// Google integration
{ school_id, mailbox }   // mailbox = masked form only if needed at warn/error level

// Auth / identity
{ user_id }   // bigint stringified — never log email, name, or role

// AI / LLM
{ model, prompt_tokens, completion_tokens, duration_ms }

// Errors — always pass the Error object as `err`, not err.message
{ err }   // pino serializes Error objects automatically (stack, message, name)
```

### PII Rules — Hard Constraints

- **Never** log email addresses in full — use `user_id` or `school_id` for correlation
- **Never** log `bodyRaw`, `bodyClean`, `subject`, or any message content
- **Never** log `Authorization` headers, bearer tokens, or `GOOGLE_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON` values
- `req_id` is safe for correlation — never log session data or cookies (redacted automatically by pino-http)

### Message Naming Convention

Messages (`msg`) should be lowercase, dot-separated, past-tense event names:

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD — consistent, greppable
logger.info({ job }, "cron.started");
logger.info({ job, duration_ms }, "cron.completed");
logger.error({ job, err }, "cron.failed");
logger.info({ school_id }, "gmail.watch.renewed");
logger.warn({ school_id }, "gmail.watch.renewal_failed");
logger.info({ port }, "server.started");
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — inconsistent, hard to filter
logger.info("Scheduler started");
logger.error(`[watch] failed to renew watch for ${email}`);
```

### In `index.ts` — Startup Log and Process Catchall

`src/index.ts` must log a structured startup event and register a single process-level catchall for unhandled rejections and uncaught exceptions:

```typescript
app.listen(port, () => {
  logger.info({ port, env: process.env["NODE_ENV"] ?? "development" }, "server.started");
  startScheduler();
});

process.on("unhandledRejection", (reason) => {
  logger.error({ err: reason }, "process.unhandledRejection");
});

process.on("uncaughtException", (err) => {
  logger.error({ err }, "process.uncaughtException");
  process.exit(1);
});
```
